      </a>
      <span style="display:block;font-family:var(--font-sans);font-size:0.6rem;font-weight:800;letter-spacing:0.2em;text-transform:uppercase;color:#f5d07a;margin-bottom:1rem;">Sellers · 6 min read</span>
      <h1 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:clamp(2rem,5vw,3.25rem);font-weight:400;color:#f0ece4;line-height:1.12;letter-spacing:-0.02em;margin-bottom:1.5rem;">
        Foreign Residents Selling Brisbane Property: CGT Withholding and What to Expect
      </h1>
      <p style="font-size:1rem;color:rgba(240,236,228,0.6);line-height:1.8;max-width:54ch;">
        If you are not an Australian tax resident when you sell, the ATO requires the buyer to withhold 12.5% of the purchase price at settlement. Here is what that means in practice and what you need to do.
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- Body -->
  <div style="padding:3rem 0 7rem;">
    <div class="max-w-[780px] mx-auto px-8" style="font-size:0.97rem;color:var(--color-text-secondary);line-height:1.9;display:flex;flex-direction:column;gap:1.75rem;">

      <p>Australia's Foreign Resident Capital Gains Withholding regime affects a broader range of property vendors than most people realise. It is not limited to overseas investors or non-citizens. It applies to anyone who is not an Australian tax resident at the time of sale, which can include Australian citizens who have been living and working abroad and have not maintained their Australian tax residency. If you are in any doubt about your residency status for tax purposes, this is an issue you need to resolve before you list your Brisbane property, not after you have signed a contract.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What the withholding regime covers</h2>
      <p>The Foreign Resident Capital Gains Withholding (FRCGW) regime requires the buyer of an Australian property to withhold 12.5% of the purchase price at settlement and remit it directly to the Australian Taxation Office. This applies when the vendor is, or the buyer reasonably believes the vendor to be, a foreign resident for Australian tax purposes. The withholding threshold is $750,000: properties below that value are exempt, though the vast majority of Brisbane inner-east properties exceed this threshold.</p>

      <p>The withheld amount is not the vendor's final tax. It is a prepayment against whatever CGT liability the vendor has on the sale. The vendor lodges an Australian tax return, the actual CGT is calculated, and any amount withheld above the actual liability is refunded. If the actual CGT exceeds the amount withheld, the balance is payable in the return. The point is that the ATO collects a prepayment upfront rather than relying on a foreign resident to lodge a return from overseas.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Who is affected</h2>
      <p>Any vendor who does not hold an ATO clearance certificate at settlement is treated as a foreign resident for the purpose of the withholding rules, and the buyer must withhold. This means that even Australian residents need to obtain a clearance certificate to avoid withholding. The clearance certificate is how you demonstrate to the buyer that you are an Australian tax resident and that the withholding obligation does not apply.</p>

      <p>Vendors who are genuinely non-resident for tax purposes cannot obtain a clearance certificate. These include overseas-based investors who own Brisbane property, Australians who have permanently relocated abroad, foreign nationals who own local property, and in some cases Australians working abroad on extended assignments depending on the specific circumstances of their residency status. The determination of tax residency is a legal question that turns on factors including physical presence, domicile, the location of your permanent home, and the continuity of your connection to Australia. It is not the same as citizenship or the currency of your Australian passport.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">The clearance certificate process for Australian residents</h2>
      <p>If you are an Australian tax resident selling a property valued above $750,000, you should apply for a clearance certificate from the ATO before you go to market. The application is made through the ATO's online portal, is free of charge, and in most cases is processed within days. Once issued, a clearance certificate has a 12-month validity period.</p>

      <p>You give the clearance certificate to the buyer before settlement. This discharges the buyer's obligation to withhold, and you receive the full proceeds at settlement. Without the certificate, the buyer is legally required to withhold 12.5% even if you are an Australian resident, because the buyer has no other way to verify your status. Recovering withheld amounts that should not have been withheld requires lodging a tax return and waiting for the ATO to process the refund, which takes time and adds friction to your post-settlement finances.</p>

      <p>The practical advice is straightforward: apply for the clearance certificate early in the selling process, well before the contract is signed. Your solicitor can assist and should be reminding you of this as a standard step in sale preparation.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">The withholding amount is not the same as the CGT liability</h2>
      <p>This is one of the most commonly misunderstood aspects of the regime. Withholding is calculated as 12.5% of the gross purchase price. CGT is calculated on the capital gain, which is the difference between the proceeds and the cost base, adjusted for any applicable discounts, capital improvements, and other eligible deductions. These are fundamentally different calculations and will produce different figures.</p>

      <p>Consider a property purchased for $600,000 and sold for $1,200,000. Withholding is $150,000 (12.5% of $1,200,000). The capital gain before discount is $600,000. If the CGT discount applies at 50%, the taxable gain is $300,000, which at a marginal rate of 45% produces a CGT liability of $135,000. In this example the amount withheld exceeds the actual CGT, so the vendor would receive a refund of $15,000 on lodging the return.</p>

      <p>In cases where the cost base is high, where significant capital improvements have been made, or where the ownership period is short, the relationship between withholding and actual CGT will vary considerably. A tax agent with experience in Australian CGT for non-residents should model the likely position before settlement so the vendor understands their actual exposure and can plan accordingly.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Implications for settlement timing and proceeds</h2>
      <p>Foreign resident vendors need to plan for the cash flow implications of withholding. Receiving 87.5% of the purchase price at settlement instead of 100% affects how much capital is available immediately. If the vendor is using proceeds to discharge a mortgage or fund a simultaneous purchase, this needs to be factored into the financial planning before contracts are exchanged. A shortfall at settlement is not a situation you want to discover on the day.</p>

      <p>Settlement timing also has implications for the tax year in which the CGT liability falls. The CGT event occurs on the date contracts are exchanged, not the settlement date. Exchanging contracts in late June versus early July can place the gain in different tax years, which affects the tax return lodgement timeline and potentially the applicable tax rates if marginal rates or other income differs between years. A tax agent can advise on whether the timing of exchange has any meaningful advantage in your situation.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What overseas-based vendors need to do before listing</h2>
      <p>If you are not an Australian tax resident and you own Brisbane property, you should engage a tax agent with specific experience in Australian CGT for non-residents before you list, not after. The preparation required includes confirming your residency status, understanding the likely CGT liability and how it compares to the withholding amount, determining whether any exemptions or concessions apply, and planning for the cash flow at settlement.</p>

      <p>The main residence exemption, which exempts a person's home from CGT, does not apply to the full gain for a non-resident vendor unless the property was your principal place of residence for the entire ownership period and you were an Australian resident for the full period of ownership. The interaction between the main residence exemption and non-resident status is a specific area where specialist advice is genuinely important and where incorrect assumptions can have significant financial consequences.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What Brisbane selling agents check when acting for a foreign resident vendor</h2>
      <p>When I am appointed as selling agent for a vendor who is, or may be, a non-resident, I raise the withholding regime in our initial conversations and recommend they get independent tax advice before we go to market. The selling agent is not the right person to advise on tax residency or CGT, but we do need to understand whether withholding applies because it affects how we communicate with buyers about the settlement process and what documentation is involved.</p>

      <p>Buyers purchasing from a foreign resident vendor will be withholding agents under the regime. Their solicitors will be aware of this. Having the vendor's solicitor and tax agent engaged early, with the residency question resolved and the withholding position confirmed, avoids complications during the contract and settlement process that could otherwise create uncertainty for buyers at a sensitive stage of negotiation.</p>

